      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics argue that substantive due process allows judges to engage in judicial activism, inventing rights not explicitly written in the text. However, defenders argue that the Constitution is not just a list of explicit rules, but a framework safeguarding fundamental human dignities. When a law violates deeply ingrained moral or personal freedoms—like privacy or bodily autonomy—courts are fulfilling their duty to uphold the foundational promise of liberty. Therefore, some judicial interpretation is necessary to ensure the Constitution remains a living guarantor of basic human rights against legislative overreach.",
      "source": "target",
